<B><FONT SIZE=4><P ALIGN="CENTER">Arithmetic Progressions</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"></P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER">Learning Plan 3</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"></P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER">Sum to n terms</P>

<P>Adding Terms</P>
</B></FONT>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>It is often of interest to add terms up.   Define S<SUB>n</SUB>, the sum of the first n terms.</P>
<P>S<SUB>1</SUB> = t<SUB>1</P>
</SUB>
<P>S<SUB>2</SUB> = t<SUB>1</SUB> + t<SUB>2</P>
</SUB>
<P>S<SUB>3</SUB> = t<SUB>1</SUB> + t<SUB>2</SUB> + t<SUB>3</P>
</SUB>
<P>Continuing in this way.</P>

<P>S<SUB>n</SUB> = t<SUB>1</SUB> + t<SUB>2</SUB>  +  t<SUB>3</SUB>  + …………+  t<SUB>n</SUB>  <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#186;</FONT>
<FONT FACE="Symbol">&#83;</FONT>
 t<SUB>i</SUB></P>
<P>Spend time on <a href="runcal.htm#==C:\CALMAT\tcrun.exe calpopup //?~ 0 3 1 e 0~?">3-1 section e</a>.   Gain confidence in using the summation sign by working on <a href="launch.htm#q0334">q0334</a> and <a href="launch.htm#q0335">q0335</a>.  
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P><B>Example</B></P>
<FONT SIZE=4>
</FONT><P>For the arithmetic progression ,</P>
<P>12, 17, 22, 27, 32, …….</P>
<P>The sum to four terms, S<SUB>4</SUB>, is :</P>

<P>S<SUB>4</SUB> = 12 + 17 + 22 + 27 = 78</P>

<P>Alternatively, S<SUB>4</SUB> can be calculated as follows:-</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P><DIR>
<DIR>

<P> S<SUB>4</SUB> = 12 + 17 + 22 + 27</P>

<P> S<SUB>4</SUB> = 27 + 22 + 17 + 12</P>
</DIR>
</DIR>

<P>Add&#9;&#9;2S<SUB>4</SUB> =39 + 39 + 39 + 39 = 156 = (4)(39)</P>

<P>Hence S<SUB>4</SUB> = 156/2 = 78  (the same result as before)</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<B><FONT SIZE=4><P>Sum to n Terms</P>
</B></FONT>
<P>By following the method of the previous example, S<SUB>n</SUB>, can be expressed as :-</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>&#9;&#9; S<SUB>n</SUB> = a&#9;&#9;&#9;+ (a+d) + ………&#9;+ (a + (n-1)d)</P>

<P>&#9;&#9; S<SUB>n</SUB> = (a + (n-1)d)&#9;+ ……&#9;&#9;&#9;+ a</P>

<P>Add&#9;&#9;2S<SUB>n</SUB> = 2a + (n-1)d&#9;+ ……&#9;&#9;&#9;+ 2a + (n-1)d</P>

<P>In the last line above, 2a + (n-1)d appears n times.</P>

<P>Hence </P>

<P>2S<SUB>n</SUB> = n(2a + (n-1)d)</P>

<br>
<P>giving <B><FONT SIZE=4>S<SUB>n</SUB> = n/2(2a + (n-1)d)
<br>
</B></FONT>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>This formula gives a mathematical way of finding S<SUB>n</SUB> if the first term, a, the common difference, d, and the number of terms, n, are known.</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>
<B><FONT SIZE=4><P>Example</P>
</B></FONT>
<P>Find the sum to forty terms of the following arithmetic progressions:</P>

<OL TYPE="a">

<LI>3,  7,  11,  15, …..</LI>

<LI>100,  98,  96,  94, ……</LI>

<LI>2,  2.5,  3,  3.5, ……</LI></OL>

<br>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<B><FONT SIZE=4><P>Solution</P>
</B></FONT>
<OL TYPE="a">

<LI>The common difference is 4.</LI>

<P>So we have a = 3,  d = 4,  n = 40.</P>

<P>S<SUB>40</SUB> = (40/2)((2)(3) + (40-1)4) = 3240</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>
<LI>The common difference is –2.</LI>

<P>So we have a = 100, d = -2, n = 40</P>

<P>S<SUB>40</SUB> = (40/2)((2)(100) + (40-1)(-2)) = 2440</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<LI>The common difference is 0.5.</LI>

<P>So we have a = 2, d = 0.5, n = 40</P>

<P>S<SUB>40</SUB> = (40/2)((2)(2) + (40-1)(0.5)) = 470</P></OL>
<P>&nbsp;</P>

<P>Try <a href="launch.htm#q0208">q0208</a>. 
</FONT>

